<cell id="cell-0"><language>kotlin</language>// Kotlin notebook
import jline.*
import jline.lang.*
import jline.lang.nodes.*
import jline.lang.processes.*
import jline.lang.constant.*
import jline.solvers.jmt.*
import jline.util.matrix.*</cell id="cell-0">
<cell id="cell-1"><language>kotlin</language>// Example: Global Class-Level Patience
//
// This example demonstrates setting patience at the job class level rather
// than per-queue. When patience is set globally on a class, it applies to
// all queues that the class visits (unless overridden by queue-specific settings).
//
// Model:
// - Three queues in series
// - Two job classes:
//   * Class 1: Global exponential patience (applies to all queues)
//   * Class 2: Global deterministic patience + queue-specific override at Queue2

val model = Network("Global Patience Example")</cell id="cell-1">
<cell id="cell-2"><language>kotlin</language>// Define nodes
val source = Source(model, "Source")
val queue1 = Queue(model, "Queue1", SchedStrategy.FCFS)
val queue2 = Queue(model, "Queue2", SchedStrategy.FCFS)
val queue3 = Queue(model, "Queue3", SchedStrategy.FCFS)
val sink = Sink(model, "Sink")

// Define job classes
val globalExpClass = OpenClass(model, "GlobalExpClass", 0)
val overrideClass = OpenClass(model, "OverrideClass", 0)</cell id="cell-2">
<cell id="cell-3"><language>kotlin</language>// Set GLOBAL patience at the class level
// This applies to ALL queues unless overridden
globalExpClass.setPatience(Exp(0.4))   // Mean patience = 2.5 everywhere
overrideClass.setPatience(Det(4.0))    // Fixed patience = 4.0 everywhere (by default)

// Set service times
queue1.setService(globalExpClass, Exp(1.0))
queue1.setService(overrideClass, Exp(1.0))
queue2.setService(globalExpClass, Exp(1.2))
queue2.setService(overrideClass, Exp(1.2))
queue3.setService(globalExpClass, Exp(0.8))
queue3.setService(overrideClass, Exp(0.8))

// Set arrival rates
source.setArrival(globalExpClass, Exp(0.3))
source.setArrival(overrideClass, Exp(0.2))</cell id="cell-3">
<cell id="cell-4"><language>kotlin</language>// Override global patience for Class 2 at Queue2 only
// This demonstrates per-queue settings taking precedence over global settings
queue2.setPatience(overrideClass, Exp(0.2))  // More impatient at Queue2</cell id="cell-4">
<cell id="cell-5"><language>kotlin</language>// Define routing
val P = model.initRoutingMatrix()

// Routing for GlobalExpClass
P.set(globalExpClass, globalExpClass, source, queue1, 1.0)   // Source -> Queue1
P.set(globalExpClass, globalExpClass, queue1, queue2, 1.0)   // Queue1 -> Queue2
P.set(globalExpClass, globalExpClass, queue2, queue3, 1.0)   // Queue2 -> Queue3
P.set(globalExpClass, globalExpClass, queue3, sink, 1.0)     // Queue3 -> Sink

// Routing for OverrideClass
P.set(overrideClass, overrideClass, source, queue1, 1.0)     // Source -> Queue1
P.set(overrideClass, overrideClass, queue1, queue2, 1.0)     // Queue1 -> Queue2
P.set(overrideClass, overrideClass, queue2, queue3, 1.0)     // Queue2 -> Queue3
P.set(overrideClass, overrideClass, queue3, sink, 1.0)       // Queue3 -> Sink

model.link(P)</cell id="cell-5">
<cell id="cell-6"><language>kotlin</language>// Solve with JMT
println("This example demonstrates global class-level patience configuration.")
println()
println("Class 1 (GlobalExpClass):")
println("  - Has exponential patience (mean = 2.5) at ALL queues (global setting)")
println()
println("Class 2 (OverrideClass):")
println("  - Has deterministic patience (timeout = 4.0) at Queue1 and Queue3 (global setting)")
println("  - Has exponential patience (mean = 5.0) at Queue2 (per-queue override)")
println()

val solver = JMT(model, "seed", 23000, "verbose", true, "keep", true, "samples", 100000)
val avgTable = solver.avgTable
avgTable.print()

println()
println("Note: Global patience settings simplify configuration when the same")
println("      patience behavior applies across multiple queues. Per-queue settings")
println("      can override global settings when needed.")</cell id="cell-6">
<cell id="cell-7"><language>markdown</language>## Global Class-Level Patience

This notebook demonstrates setting patience at the **job class level** rather than per-queue. When patience is configured globally on a class, it automatically applies to all queues that the class visits, unless overridden by queue-specific settings.

### Model Structure
- **Three queues in series**: Queue1 → Queue2 → Queue3
- **Two job classes** with different patience configurations:
  - **GlobalExpClass**: Exponential patience (mean = 2.5) at all queues
  - **OverrideClass**: Deterministic patience (timeout = 4.0) everywhere, except Queue2

### Patience Configuration Hierarchy
1. **Global setting**: Set on the job class, applies to all queues
2. **Per-queue override**: Set on specific queue-class pairs, overrides global setting

### Example Configuration
- **GlobalExpClass**:
  - Global patience: Exp(0.4) → mean patience = 2.5 at all queues

- **OverrideClass**:
  - Global patience: Det(4.0) → fixed timeout = 4.0 at Queue1 and Queue3
  - Queue2 override: Exp(0.2) → mean patience = 5.0 at Queue2 only

### Use Cases
Global patience settings are useful when:
- The same patience behavior applies across multiple queues
- You want to model customer patience as a class characteristic
- You need simpler configuration for large networks

Per-queue overrides are useful when:
- Specific queues have different service expectations
- Some queues are more critical than others
- You need fine-grained control over abandonment behavior</cell id="cell-7">